            <!-- THE HISTORY Content -->
            <h3>The History</h3>
            <p>Economic development has always been determined by one critical factor: <strong>control of capital</strong>. Those who control capital decide what gets built, who gets funded, and which societies advance. In the modern global system, this power has largely been concentrated in financial institutions that have historically overlooked Africa, despite its strong economic potential.</p>
            
            <p>This same pattern of exclusion once existed in the United States. In the early 20th century, African Americans faced systemic denial of access to capital, markets, and economic opportunity. Rather than accept this condition, they built their own economic system — known as <strong>Black Wall Street</strong>.</p>
            
            <p>It was not just a business district; it was a fully functional economic ecosystem. Residents owned banks, retail stores, transportation systems, and real estate. Money circulated within the community, creating jobs, wealth, and independence. This system demonstrated a timeless economic truth: <em>when people control their capital, they control their future</em>.</p>
            
            <p>However, this success was violently disrupted in 1921 when the entire community was destroyed. What followed was not just physical loss, but the dismantling of a functioning model of economic independence. The legacy of Black Wall Street remains one of the clearest historical proofs that structured economic cooperation can produce large-scale prosperity. Today, that model is being rebuilt in a modern form, adapted for Africa's scale, population, and technological environment.</p>
            
